Lawsuits alleged that Trump violated the Domestic and Foreign Emoluments Clauses of the U.S. Constitution.[258] The plaintiffs said that Trump's business interests could allow foreign governments to influence him.[258][257][259][260] NBC News reported in 2019 that representatives of at least 22 foreign governments, including some facing charges of corruption or human rights abuses, appeared to have spent money at Trump Organization businesses during his presidency.[261][262] The litigation marked the first time that the Emoluments Clauses were substantively litigated.[258][260] As president, Trump mocked the Emoluments Clause as "phony."[263][257] In January 2021, the U.S. Supreme Court dismissed the lawsuits as Trump was no longer president.[264]
